dslRuleAfterChange:
A hypothetical rule might look like (demonstrates required features, not exact syntax):

// Metadata for the rule
<!id: implement-iadaptable>
<!description: Implement IAdaptable and add getAdapter method for Program field>
<!severity: info>
<!minJavaVersion: 8>
<!tags: eclipse-api, adaptation, code-structure>

// Pattern: A class that has a 'Program program' field and doesn't implement IAdaptable
class $ClassName extends $SuperType {
    org.eclipse.swt.program.Program $programField;
    // ... other members ...
} :: !inClass("org.eclipse.core.runtime.IAdaptable") // Simplified check
=>
// Replacement: Add IAdaptable and the getAdapter method
class $ClassName extends $SuperType implements org.eclipse.core.runtime.IAdaptable {
    org.eclipse.swt.program.Program $programField;
    // ... other members ...

    @java.lang.Override
    public <T> T getAdapter(java.lang.Class<T> adapter) {
        if (adapter == org.eclipse.swt.program.Program.class) {
            return adapter.cast($programField);
        }
        return null;
    }
}
;;

This rule would require sophisticated AST manipulation capabilities to detect the presence of a 'program' field and inject a new method with an 'if' block that references that field. This is not just a 'Yellow' minor extension, but a 'RED' major overhaul of DSL capabilities.

A hypothetical DSL syntax might look like:

// Add a guard to prevent menu display if 'NoMenu' tag is present
// This is NOT supported by the current DSL due to multi-statement replacement
// and insertion of control flow.

@MenuDetectListener
$tb.addMenuDetectListener(e -> {
    // Match the entire lambda body or a statement within it
    $existingStatements$
}) :: hasParentType($existingStatements$, "org.eclipse.e4.ui.workbench.addons.perspectiveswitcher.PerspectiveSwitcher")
=>
$tb.addMenuDetectListener(e -> {
    if (perspSwitcherToolControl.getTags().contains("NoMenu")) {
        return;
    }
    $existingStatements$
})
;;

Alternatively, a different approach might be needed to allow insertion of 'if' statements before a matched expression. This kind of transformation is more complex than simple expression-to-expression or annotation-to-annotation rewrites.
